      </div>
      <h1 class='title'>When pension sharing orders may take effect</h1>
    </div>
    <div class='grand-committee-report-sitting' id='content'>
      
      <cite class='section'>HL Deb 17 May 2004 vol 661 c274GC</cite>
      <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_274gc' title='Col. 274GC &mdash; HL Deb 17 May 2004 vol 661 c274GC' name='column_274gc' href='#column_274gc' rel='bookmark'>274GC</a>
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0661P0-03633'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040517_GCR_244' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        14 (1) A pension sharing order is not to take effect unless the dissolution or nullity order on or after which it is made has been made final.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0661P0-03634'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040517_GCR_245' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (2) No pension sharing order may be made so as to take effect before the end of such period after the making of the order as may be prescribed by regulations made by the Lord Chancellor.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0661P0-03635'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040517_GCR_246' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (3) The power to make regulations under sub-paragraph (2) is exercisable by statutory rule for the purposes of the Statutory Rules (Northern Ireland) Order 1979 (S.I. 1979/1573 (N.I. 12)).
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0661P0-03636'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040517_GCR_247' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (4) Regulations under sub-paragraph (2) are subject to annulment in pursuance of a resolution of either House of Parliament in the same manner as a statutory instrument; and section 5 of the <a href="/acts/statutory-instruments-act-1946">Statutory Instruments Act 1946</a> (c. 36) applies accordingly.
      </p>
      <ol class='xoxo'>
        
